<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#871f78">Originally posted by Fluvius on 11-05-2000 06:23 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Several good points have been made.

For starters, it's always grated on me that Everquest was, well, EVERquest. Nothing really changed that much. If the Freeport Militia and the paladins were really at war with the orcs and each other, it was a complete and total stalemate. And no matter how many of us wiped out the dozen orc camps on Antonica, the damned orcs would keep coming from SOMEWHERE....

So, even though I was running through Lesser Faydark recently and the brownie scout dropped me like a bad habit, I appreciated the content change. Because, yes, maybe the trolls SHOULD occupy Ak'Anon for a month, shake things up. We're supposed to be adventuring, here -- not working, not farming, not squatting, and definitely not camping the same damn guard for five levels.

As noted by others above, it's all well and good that the demigod PCs get new content, but new content should be cooked up for everyone. In defense of Verant (gasp!), they have given everyone something new lately, with the new trade skills patches. Which brings me to my next point:

I work nights in RL, full-time. Meaning I sleep days. Meaning I may very well be Level 30 FOREVER.

And I don't mind. I can work on trade skills. Or scour Norrath for places a 30 rogue can solo, because it's hard finding a group at 3 a.m. PST. Or I can just see sights or help newbies.

The most inspiring EQ thing that happened to me was simply stumbling across the damned waterfall in East Karana for the first time earlier this week. I didn't even know the damn thing was there. For 30 levels I had just run from the canyons to the bridge, trying not to die or hurrying somewhere. But 15 minutes of pointless exploration, and wow. Discovering that HUGE waterfall made me feel like a newbie again.

THAT I think is what is inspiring about EQ -- the wonder of discovery. Whether it's meeting fellow adventurers or exploring dangerous lands, or learning new skills. And Verant, bless their soulless, corporate, nerfing, uber-catering heart, has done better at providing opportunities for wonder than we give them credit for.

But don't ever let up on the bastards, because now that I've got the Burning Rapier, Journeyman's Boots and a full set of pre-epic quest ravenscale (sans the dorky helmet) I could USE a good challenge....

That's my 2,000,000 cp on this subject.

------------------
Fluvius Rex of Freeport
Founder, the Guild With No Name
Rogue of 30 seasons
Proud Citizen of Torvonnilous</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
